post_text:
Many of you were hoping to attend this evening's home football game and to celebrate Senior Night. Tickets for General Admission were sold out within minutes of going on sale this morning. If you were unable to purchase a ticket for tonight's game, we know you are disappointed and frustrated. We completely understand and we are just as frustrated! This situation is a result of the capacity restrictions placed on our athletic facilities by ODH & the OHSAA. Schools are only allowed to fill 15% of the seats in their athletic facilities due to the COVID-19 protocols. We truly wish we could fill our entire football stadium, but these strict requirements prevent us from doing so.
If you would like to watch the game from home, please know it will be live-streamed through Chatterbox Sports. Kickoff at 7 pm. Here's how you can watch the game:
Step 1: Go to http://watchchatterbox.com/
Step 2: Click LOGIN in top right corner
Step 3: Click SIGNUP if you don't have a subscription already
Step 4: Once logged in, click Live+ at the top to get to the games for tonight

post_text: When Ava Fulks, a 3rd Grader at EES, heard the news about Middletown Police Officer Jordan & K9 Koda being involved a recent confrontation where Officer Jordan was shot, she wanted her classmates & Buttercup pledges to do something inspiring for them. Ava had previously worked with Officer Jordan on a recent fundraiser for the Middletown K9 Unit. Ava & Brylee Simpson, also from EES, along with members of the Buttercup Pledges from the Rainbow Girls Middletown Masonic lodge, delivered a special gift along with cards of support & well-wishes to Officer Jordan & K9 Koda. The cards were created by students in Mrs. Dent & Mrs. Tilton's class at EES. Edgewood is so proud of these students! Thank you for your kindness, caring spirit for others & genuine support. Your actions show your commitment to living our Cougar Character Traits!

post_text: We are so proud of one of our EES students, Michael Lipp, who was honored by the Trenton Fire Department with a Life Saving Medal for his actions in saving his grandmother's life. Michael was at his grandmother's home when she suddenly had a medical emergency Michael promptly dialed 911 for help. Without his quick action, she would not have received the immediate medical attention that was needed. Michael bravely remained calm & in turn, his actions saved his grandmother's life. You are truly a hero, Michael!!!

post_text:
We are excited to welcome back our students in just a couple of weeks! Be sure your student's immunizations are up-to-date before the start of school. Here’s a list of immunizations organized by a student’s grade level. https://5il.co/jmv1

A reminder to any 7th Grader, who needs to get a Tdap and/or Meningococcal vaccine, please take care of this before school. Likewise, any 12th Grader who needs a meningococcal vaccine should take care of getting this scheduled before school starts.

All other immunizations must be completed by the 14th day of school or your child may be excluded from attending. If your child has a medical condition that prevents him/her from taking an immunization OR if you have a religious or philosophical objection to vaccines, please see your building’s nurse to complete necessary paperwork, once school begins.

post_text:
Preschool Registration will take place tomorrow morning, June 10, at the Edgewood Central Registration Office from 8:00 a.m. - 10:00 a.m. This is an in-person registration. Registration fees are due at the time of registration. Fee is $280 ($250 for first month's tuition & $30 school fees) to hold your place for the 2020-21 school year. Children do not need to be present. Parents are asked to wear a mask & practice social distancing. Parents must have the child's birth certificate, immunization record, parent photo ID, proof of residency, and custody documents (if applicable).
Applicants for Preschool Registration are considered on a first come, first serve basis based on availability. Once the program is at full capacity, applicants will be placed on a waiting list.

post_text:
Preschool Registration will take place at the Edgewood Central Registration Office on Wednesday, June 10, 2020, from 8:00 a.m. - 10:00 a.m. This is an in-person registration. Registration fees are due at the time of registration. Fee is $280 ($250 for first month's tuition & $30 school fees) to hold your place for the 2020-21 school year. Children do not need to be present. Parents are asked to wear a mask & practice social distancing. Parents must have the child's birth certificate, immunization record, parent photo ID, proof of residency, and custody documents (if applicable).
Applicants for Preschool Registration are considered on a first come, first serve basis based on availability. Once the program is at full capacity, applicants will be placed on a waiting list.

post_text:
Edgewood off-season training will begin on Monday, June 1. The training plans have been approved by our district's administration & communicated to your son or daughter's coaching staff. As a district, we have followed recommended guidelines by state and local authorities, keeping in mind that student safety is our top priority. At this time, we are unsure what the state has in store for fall competition; however, there are some things that we can take a proactive approach to:
1. OHSAA has issued the continuance of physical evaluations for all students in grades 7-12
2. Final Forms are open for registration for fall sports https://edgewood-oh.finalforms.com/parents/login

OHSAA has also agreed to waive academic eligibility for all 2020 fall sports for students entering grades 7-12.

post_text: Distance learning did not slow down Hunter Ferrell, a 2nd Grade student from EES, from achieving his goal of reaching 150 "STAR" Accelerated Reader Points! He continued reading books & taking quizzes from home since school has been out. To earn STAR Accelerated Reader points, a student reads a book and then takes a comprehensive quiz on the story. If most of the questions are answered correctly, the student will earn points. A short storybook is only worth 0.5 points so it takes a long time to reach each new level. We are so excited for Hunter and achieving his goal! Congratulations Hunter! We are so proud of you!

post_text: Future Cougars! Edgewood is using a new process for registering kindergartners for next fall. Beginning today, May 6- June 12, any parent wishing to register their child for Kindergarten must call our Central Registration Office to begin the process. Call (513) 867-3416, from 8 am- 3:30 pm, Mondays, Wednesdays, and Fridays to schedule an appointment. The Central Registration Office will provide you with the additional information on how to complete the registration process. (FYI- Preschool Registration has not yet been announced. Once it has been rescheduled, we will announce information on social media & our website).

Today, March 30, 2020, Governor Mike DeWine made an announcement extending his March 12 order for all of Ohio’s public, community, and private K-12 school buildings to remain closed to students through Friday, May 1, 2020. We know the extension of the Governor’s school closure presents a challenge to our families. Our district is working diligently to partner with our families in furthering your child’s education and well-being. We are experiencing a health crisis that none of us has experienced in our lifetime. Luckily, the Edgewood community is strong and united. Together, we will navigate through this challenging situation.

We have answers to your frequently asked questions here: https://bit.ly/2UuKAHy

All Edgewood City Schools will be closed starting Monday, March 16 until Tuesday, April 14. This necessary action is an effective public health strategy to disrupt widespread infection of the Coronavirus.

Effective immediately, March 12, ALL district activities are cancelled until further notice. This includes: athletics/sports, practices, games, enrichment, performances, PTO and community group meetings, spaghetti dinner, sports banquets, fundraisers, field trips, etc. For complete details, click here: http://bit.ly/2U4KBjW

post_text: Congratulations to Hunter Ferrell, EES 2nd Grader, for scoring 106 points on his STAR Accelerated Reading program. His score is the highest anyone has received in 2nd Grade at EES! Since August, he's read 150 books & has taken a quiz after reading each book, earning him 106 points towards the STAR AR program. His goal is to reach 150 points by the end of May. Great job & good luck Hunter! Edgewood is very proud of you and your accomplishment!

post_text: Our EES 2nd & 3rd Grade students spent the afternoon reading with our EHS student-athletes. EES was sent 1,000 Hog Mollies books from @The2ndand7Foundation. The themes in these books reiterate valuable life lessons. The mission of @The2ndand7Foundation is to promote reading by providing free books & positive role models to kids in need while encouraging young athletes within the community to pay it forward. At the end of the day, each Little Cougar was given a book to take home. It was a great opportunity to remind all our kids how important it is to read as well as celebrate National Read Across America Day!

post_text: Our 1st EHS Cougar College & Career Fair took place this morning & it was a great sucess! Over 30 businesses & job placement companies, 10 colleges & 5 different branches of the military were at EHS to talk to our seniors. Opportunities for jobs, internships, apprenticeships, assistance with college applications as well as careers in the military were shared with our students. It was tremendously helpful for many as they plan for “life after Edgewood”! Thank You to all the recruiters who participated in our event. Your time & interest in our students’ future is greatly appreciated. And, Thank You to our counselors & staff for making this event possible!

post_text: Students in Ms. Sanders Government classes have been studying about the Civil Rights Movement during Black History Month. These EHS students were challenged to develop a method on how they could share information about the Civil Rights Movement with students at EES. Their efforts resulted in developing 10 different interactive activities that would teach students about this pivotal event in our country's history. Using familiar games as the basis for how the information was presented, 4th and 5th grade students were able to learn about this event. Likewise, our EHS students recognized that through creating the activities for the EES students, they also learned a tremendous amount about Black History and the Civil Rights Movement. It was an amazing learning experience for everyone.

post_text: Our Edgewood/Butler Tech FFA hosted the National FFA Officer team today. The officers presented workshops & keynote speeches to all our Butler Tech classes, as well as to FFA members from Ross & Talawanda. As part of the day's activities, student representatives from all the local FFA chapters presented a check to the Puerto Rico FFA to assist with earthquake relief efforts. One of the National FFA Officers, Yomar Roman, is from Puerto Rico. He was deeply touched by this generous gift & shared his heartfelt thanks to everyone on behalf of those impacted by these disasters.

post_text:
Safety drill will continue through February 13 at Edgewood City Schools. These drills have been scheduled to ensure students and staff members are prepared in the event of an active and aggressive emergency situation. Our drills will be conducted in partnership with the Butler County Sheriff Office and the Trenton Police Department.

It is important you know these drills are planned. This precaution is being taken so that anyone who overhears any conversation, receives text messages or emails about a drill would not mistake it as a real world emergency. Once a drill starts, any communications will begin and end with "This is a drill" so all participants know the communication is related to the planned drill. In the event a real world emergency would occur during a drill, the phrase, "Real World Emergency" will be issued over our communication systems.
